flowRoot.flowPara: Rich Miller, ideas & data mostly from LaFontaine, keys from Wiggins (9/7/2015)

Codes: L-larva, D-drift (submerged), A-accidental, B-behavioral, R-rappel, N-naked, C-cased, __-Pupation, di-diapause, M-migrate, P-pherate, X-eclose (escape from pherate skin), Rz-rise (swimming/buoyed), E-emerge (through the film or onto the bank), F-float (on surface), O-oviposit, Ex-expire, followed by loc or time indicator in parens. Starred-more important to fishers. Type faces: BOLD-important, REGULAR-possible, SMALLER-informational.

Matching caddis is more complicated than matching mayflies. This is mostly because of temporal disconnects. Larval availability is detached by weeks or months from emergence by diapause and pupation, and egg laying often follows days or weeks after the pherates eclose.

The emergence signal itself is often obscure. No ripening nymphs appear in your kick net. Instead, pherates (essentially cellophane-wrapped adults) chew out of their cocoon and those of most families soon rise to drift just awash, invisible to the fisher, then quickly eclose and flitter off, directly out of the shuck. You need to look closely to spot the takeoff. Pherates from other families swim and crawl onto shore or exposed objects and eclose only once they are out of the water. But since they typically do this at dusk or in the dark, again the emergence is not apparent. Only a few caddis emergers (none on our list) mark their advent by skittering or crawling along the surface where they can be easily seen.
After emergence, caddis flittering near the water are mostly just hanging out or drinking, and when they touch down, they do so too briefly to excite selective trout feeding.
Only during oviposition do you see obvious signs - upstream flying swarms, lots of bobbing or crashing, and expired females, and sometimes males, floating on the surface.

Nonetheless, there are efficient fishing strategies. You can fish the larvae like you do mayfly nymphs - turn up rocks or use a kick net to find active or drifting individuals, or visually locate fixed or crawling cased ones, and imitate what you find with bottom or buffer layer drifts.

If you find sealed cases or stone domes attached to substrate, the caddis are pupating (so you can forget the larvae) and you know there is now or will eventually be an emergence. You can search the bushes or capture flying adults to find what caddis may still emerge or will oviposit. Both activities let you plan ahead.

If you detect the signs of a surface caddis emergence in progress: according to LaFontaine - 1) an occasional jumping rise, 2) frequent bulging or pyramidal splashing rises, and 3) no obvious insects on the water, try to capture an individual (floating cripples may be your best bet), then fish an awash emerger imitation, twitch and drift. If you can't find a sample, try likely sizes and colors until something works. If an emergence is not yet in progress, but you expect one, dead drift a deep pherate.
When nothing special is happening, search the water where the caddis hang out with a downwing dry.
Finally, if the caddis are ovipositing, grab a corpse, and smack down or dap a dry or flashy wet.

As with mayflies, there are two distinct modes of emergence, one where the number of days on any given reach is short, but rolls upriver, and to other higher waters, and the other where the emergence remains in place, often day after day (with missed days due to poor conditions) for months. When the situation is clear, I depict the latter with broken timelines. Caddis that undergo diapause typically have concentrated emergences, with peaks lasting a few days or a week.

Miscellaneous: For most families, pupation lasts a couple of weeks. Because of mass lost during pupation, adults are 1-2 hook sizes smaller than larvae. Since adults can drink, they live longer, allowing broader mating periods, thus extended emergence. Caddis have no tails. Adult antennae can be very long, but on larvae they are just tiny stubs, frequently invisible without magnification.
